      "text": "In the case of more than one product, ‘subadditivity refers to a situation in which a single firm is able to exploit both economies of scale and economies of scope and hence produce any combination of the same listing of goods more cheaply than the same listing of goods could be produced by any alternative industry configuration of more than one firm’.73 If the condition of subadditivity holds, the market only supports a single firm supplying the good. ([[Marco Weiss]] (2007). [[Efficient Organizational Design]], p. 56)"
